---
description: Frontend rules
globs: frontend/**
---

Use React + Vite + TypeScript.

Use React Router for pages and routing.

Use Leaflet / OpenStreetMap for map functionality.

Use CSS Modules for component styles.
Each styled component should have its own `*.module.css` file.
Do not use large global CSS files for component styling.
Global CSS may contain only reset, root variables, and base layout styles.

Light and dark theme (required):
- Follow the system theme via `prefers-color-scheme` — do not hardcode colors for only one mode.
- Define shared tokens in `src/styles/global.css` (`--color-bg`, `--color-surface`, `--color-text`, `--color-primary`, `--color-primary-contrast`, `--color-border`, `--color-hover-bg`, etc.) and reuse them in CSS Modules.
- When adding or changing UI styles, verify both light and dark appearance before finishing.
- Avoid fixed `#fff` / `#000` for text on themed surfaces; use `--color-text`, `--color-primary-contrast`, or other semantic variables.
- Form controls (`input`, `select`, `textarea`, buttons) must remain readable in both themes (background, border, hover, focus).
- Native controls in dark mode: set `color-scheme: dark` under `@media (prefers-color-scheme: dark)` where appropriate.

Responsive sizing (required — mobile, tablet, desktop):
- Do not use fixed `px` for layout, spacing, typography, or map marker dimensions.
- Prefer `rem`, `em`, `%`, `vh`/`vw`, and `clamp()` for sizes that must scale across devices.
- Define related sizes as CSS custom properties on the component container (for example `--map-marker-outer` on the map root).
- Use `clamp(min-rem, preferred-vw, max-rem)` when a size should grow on larger screens but stay usable on phones.
- Allowed `px` exceptions only: `1px` borders/outlines, hairline dividers, and third-party library requirements that cannot be expressed in CSS — in that case derive px from computed styles at runtime, never hardcode marker or layout sizes in JavaScript.
- Leaflet / map markers: style circles with rem/clamp in CSS; if `iconSize` / `iconAnchor` need numbers, read sizes via `getComputedStyle` or a small helper (see `src/utils/mapMarkerSize.ts`), and refresh on resize/orientation change.
- After changing map or UI dimensions, verify on a narrow viewport (mobile width), not only desktop.

Use React Hook Form + Zod for forms and validation.
Do not use Formik.

Keep API calls in a separate service layer, for example `src/services/api.ts`.

Keep shared TypeScript interfaces/types in a separate folder, for example `src/types/`.

Main public pages:
- public map page
- report form page
- success page
- error page

Main admin pages:
- admin login page
- admin light points table page
- add/edit light point page
- import/export page

Public frontend requirements:
- show street light addresses from the database (`light_points.address`), filled once via backend geocoding script — do not call Nominatim on every map popup or page load
- allow search by address, street, or inventory number
- allow selecting an existing street light
- allow selecting custom location outside known street lights
- prefill available street light data after selecting a point
- allow manual editing before sending
- show form compatible with DPMK/AUSEMIO
- support phone and email validation
- support fault type selection
- support custom text for other fault type
- support one or more photo attachments
- show clear success or error result after sending

Do not implement citizen registration.

Do not store citizen personal data in frontend storage such as localStorage or sessionStorage.

Keep components small, readable, and typed.
